description.narrative: (Rwanda): USAID's Gimbuka (Be Resilient) Program supports Rwanda's efforts to address chronic malnutrition. With FY 2018 funds, USAID through Caritas Rwanda will improve the nutritional status of women and children, especially those under two years in Ruhango district and select administrative sectors in eight other districts, through community-based nutrition behavior change interventions. The funding will address issues around poor complementary feeding practices among children under five years of age and pregnant lactating women. This will be achieved through a positive deviance hearth model, where caretakers of well-nourished children will mentor families with moderately malnourished children to adopt healthy feeding practices and dietary diversity. Gimbuka will reach a total of 89,681 children under five with growth monitoring and promotion, and implement water, sanitation and hygiene (WASH) interventions (e.g. handwashing, safe water use, latrine cleanliness) to prevent diarrheal diseases. With Maternal and Child Health (MCH) funds, Gimbuka will promote maternal health by encouraging pregnant women to attend at least four antenatal care visits at health facilities, and providing nutrition counseling and cooking demonstration lessons to promote a healthy and safe pregnancy. .Gimbuka's community-based approach ensures USAID reaches the most vulnerable women and children, empowering them to adopt healthier feeding and improved sanitation practices. Gimbuka directly contributes to the Country Development Cooperation Strategy (CDCS) goal of improving the health and nutrition status of Rwandans. ..
